R Notebook, based on depth_model_fit.R but for Royal Interface

[1] The relationship between variable (Y) and depth (Z) can be explained by four models

Model 1 (exponential decay): Y = a * exp(b * Z)

Model 2 (power law): Y = a * (Z/Z0)^b

Model 3 (exponential with fixed point): Y = Y(Z0) * exp(b * (Z - Z0))

Model 4 (power law with fixed point): Y = Y(Z0) * (Z/Z0)^b

[1.1] Definitions of functions

#Give the data frame, the variables you wish to plot against depth, and the starting depth into this function
depth.model <- function(data, variable, start.depth)
{
  #Get the data of depth as Z, and selected variable as Y, both starting from the starting depth
  Z = data$depth[data$depth >= start.depth]              
  logZ = log(Z)
  Y = data[, variable + 3][data$depth >= start.depth]
  logY = log(Y)
  
  #Get the starting point (Z0 and Y(Z0)) for model 3 and 4 as Z0 and Y0
  Z0 = Z[1]
  Y0 = Y[1]
  
  #Fit model 1 as: log(Y) = log(a) + b * Z
  model1 = lm(logY ~ Z)
  
  #Fit model 2 as: log(Y) = log(a) + b * log(Z)
  model2 = lm(logY ~ logZ)
  
  #Fit model 3 as: log(Y) - log(Y(Z0)) = b * (Z - Z0)
  model3 = lm(I(logY-log(Y0)) ~ I(Z-Z0) - 1)
  
  #Fit model 4 as: log(Y) - log(Y(Z0)) = b * (log(Z) - log(Z0)) 
  model4 = lm(I(logY - log(Y0)) ~ I(logZ - log(Z0)) - 1)
  
  #Plot and visualize the model fitting results
  plot(Y ~ Z,log = 'xy', pch = 19, type = 'o',cex = 0.8)
  #curve(exp(model1$coef[1])*exp(model1$coef[2]*x),add=T,col='red')
  #curve(exp(model2$coef[1])*x^(model2$coef[2]),add=T,col='green')
  curve(Y0*exp(model3$coef[1]*(x - Z0)), add = T, col = 'blue')
  curve(Y0*(x/Z0)^(model4$coef[1]),add = T, col = 'orange')
  legend('topright', c("model 1","model 2","model 3","model 4"), lty = 1, col = c('red','green','blue','orange'))
  
  #Report coefficients and R-square values 
  cat("Model 1: a = ",exp(model1$coef[1]),", b = ",model1$coef[2],", R-square = ",summary(model1)$r.squared,'\n')
  cat("Model 2: a = ",exp(model2$coef[1])*(Z0^model2$coef[2]),", b = ",model2$coef[2],", R-square = ",summary(model2)$r.squared,'\n')
  cat("Model 3: Y(Z0) = ",Y0,", b = ",model3$coef[1],", R-square = ",summary(model3)$r.squared,'\n')
  cat("Model 4: Y(Z0) = ",Y0,", b = ",model4$coef[1],", R-square = ",summary(model4)$r.squared,'\n')
  cat("The best model based on R-square is: Model ",which.max(c(summary(model1)$r.squared,summary(model2)$r.squared,summary(model3)$r.squared,summary(model4)$r.squared)),'\n')
}

#modified function
depth_normalized.model <- function(data,variable,start.depth)
{
  #Get the data of depth as Z, and selected variable as Y, both starting from the starting depth
  Z = data$depth[data$depth >= start.depth]              
  logZ = log(Z)
  Y = data[,variable+3][data$depth >= start.depth]
  Y = Y/Y[1]  #mornalization
  logY = log(Y)
  
  #Get the starting point (Z0 and Y(Z0)) for model 3 and 4 as Z0 and Y0
  Z0 = Z[1]
  Y0 = Y[1]
  
  #Fit model 1 as: log(Y) = log(a) + b * Z
  model1 = lm(logY ~ Z)
  
  #Fit model 2 as: log(Y) = log(a) + b * log(Z)
  model2 = lm(logY ~ logZ)
  
  #Fit model 3 as: log(Y) - log(Y(Z0)) = b * (Z - Z0)
  model3 = lm(I(logY - log(Y0)) ~ I(Z - Z0) - 1)
  
  #Fit model 4 as: log(Y) - log(Y(Z0)) = b * (log(Z) - log(Z0)) 
  model4 = lm(I(logY - log(Y0)) ~ I(logZ - log(Z0)) - 1)
  
  #Plot and visualize the model fitting results
  plot(Y ~ Z, log = 'xy', pch = 19, type = 'o', cex = 0.8)
  #curve(exp(model1$coef[1])*exp(model1$coef[2]*x),add=T,col='red')
  #curve(exp(model2$coef[1])*x^(model2$coef[2]),add=T,col='green')
  curve(Y0*exp(model3$coef[1]*(x - Z0)), add = T, col = 'blue')
  curve(Y0*(x/Z0)^(model4$coef[1]), add = T, col = 'orange')
  #legend('topright',c("model 1","model 2","model 3","model 4"),lty=1,col=c('red','green','blue','orange'))
  
  #Report coefficients and R-square values 
  cat("Model 1: a = ",exp(model1$coef[1]),", b = ",model1$coef[2],", R-square = ",summary(model1)$r.squared,'\n')
  cat("Model 2: a = ",exp(model2$coef[1])*(Z0^model2$coef[2]),", b = ",model2$coef[2],", R-square = ",summary(model2)$r.squared,'\n')
  cat("Model 3: Y(Z0) = ",Y0,", b = ",model3$coef[1],", R-square = ",summary(model3)$r.squared,'\n')
  cat("Model 4: Y(Z0) = ",Y0,", b = ",model4$coef[1],", R-square = ",summary(model4)$r.squared,'\n')
  cat("The best model based on R-square is: Model ",which.max(c(summary(model1)$r.squared,summary(model2)$r.squared,summary(model3)$r.squared,summary(model4)$r.squared)),'\n')
}

linear-dependencypower law fitting

POC_exp <- function(x) 1.0*exp(-0.001961488*(x-Z0_POC))
POC_power <- function(x) 1.0*(x/Z0_POC)^-1.281864
POC0_exp <- function(x) 1.0*exp(-0.008991741*(x-Z0_POC0))

totalB0_power <- function(x) 1.0*(x/Z0_totalB0)^-3.047193
